    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "nitrogren makes sense. i think i might have used too much compost last year so maybe it's all washed out now. i was thinking about adding some epsom salt or maybe adjusting the pH with sulfur to help the plant absorb more. do you think changing the pH will actually help with the nitrogen issue or will it just make things more complicated?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Epsom salts and sulfur for pH adjustment are things you'll want to approach with caution, especially when dealing with a nitrogen issue. While adjusting pH can certainly help plants absorb nutrients, it's a complex process, and messing with it without knowing your soil's current reading could be more trouble than it's worth. It's much safer to first address the nitrogen directly, perhaps with a targeted nitrogen boost, before trying to fine-tune the soil's chemistry.\n\nThink of it this way: if your tomato plant is starving for nitrogen, adding sulfur to change the soil's mood might be like trying to teach a hungry baby to sing opera—it won't solve the immediate hunger problem. You need to feed the plant first, and *then* you can worry about optimizing the environment.\n\nIf you suspect the compost has leached out all the good stuff, a liquid feed is a quick fix, but if you want a long-term fix, a slow-release granular fertilizer is better than just throwing more compost on top. Just be careful not to overdo it, or you'll end up with a fertilizer burn, which is just as bad as a shortage!\n\nI've seen some",
