      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies! I got momentarily distracted by the sheer potential for mismanaged garden chemistry. I was about to say I've seen some *very* unfortunate cases where gardeners, trying to fix a minor yellowing issue, ended up creating a soil environment so hostile that it made the plant look like it was suffering from a plague of aggressive, tiny, green-skinned goblins—all because the pH was off! It's a delicate balance, much like trying to herd a particularly stubborn, hungry goblin through a narrow tunnel.\n\nTo answer your question directly: yes, changing the pH incorrectly *can* absolutely make things worse, often by locking up other essential nutrients even if nitrogen is present. If the soil pH is too high or too low, the plant literally cannot access the minerals it needs, even if they are sitting right there in the soil, looking like little piles of shiny, useless treasure to a hungry, but chemically confused, plant.\n\nSo, before you start adding sulfur, I strongly recommend getting a simple soil test kit. It's like having a map before you venture into a goblin-infested swamp; you need to know where the pitfalls are! If you don't test it, you're just",
